title.narrative: 4.2 IMPROVED KNOWLEDGE, SKILLS AND CAPACITY TO PREVENT AND RESPOND TO VIOLENCE AN

description.narrative: 4.2 Children, families/caregivers, teachers, communities and state institutions have improved knowledge, skills and capacity to prevent and respond to violence and exploitation of children, which contributes to Harmful Practices (Fgm/C And Child Marriage), Prevention Of Harmful Practice, Prevention Of Harmful Practice (Covid), Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, children and adolescents have improved protection from all forms of violence, abuse and exploitation.

title.narrative: 4.2 Children, families/caregivers, teachers, communities and state institutions have improved knowledge, skills and capacity toprevent and respond to violence and exploitation of children

description.narrative: UNICEF supported technical and operational capacity to address systemic and pandemic-induced child protection risks by: building individual, community and institutional capacities, ;strengthening ;alert mechanisms, including helplines, preventing and responding to threats to family-based care, violence/exploitation, early marriage. 4459 children (2501 girls) were reached with care support; and UNICEF reached 50% of the country’s one-stop GBV centers with interventions aiming at making services more child sensitive and enhanced prevention and response to child labour. Specific focus was placed in 20201 on preventing child sexual abuse. UNICEF leverage digital platforms to enhance capacity-building of communities, institutional service providers and policy makers. ; | Status:Met | As-of Date:04/01/2022
